---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Dr. Paul Oliver | Brenkley Doctoral College" description="Profile of Dr. Paul Oliver, Head of Research at Brenkley Doctoral College and doctoral supervisor in business management, innovation, and knowledge management.">

  <section class="py-16 px-6">
    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto">

      <a href="/supervisors" class="text-accent hover:underline text-sm mb-8 inline-block">&larr; Back to Supervisors</a>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-12">

        <!-- Sidebar -->
        <div class="md:col-span-1">
          <div class="card mb-6">
            <h1 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-1">Dr. Paul Oliver</h1>
            <p class="text-accent font-medium mb-4">Head of Research</p>
            <div class="space-y-2 text-sm text-muted">
              <p><strong class="text-foreground">Specialisms:</strong> Business Management, Innovation, Knowledge Management</p>
              <p><strong class="text-foreground">Methods:</strong> Mixed methods (quantitative survey, case study, action research)</p>
              <p><strong class="text-foreground">Active researchers:</strong> 5</p>
              <p><strong class="text-foreground">Capacity:</strong> Open to new enquiries</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="card mb-6">
            <h2 class="font-bold mb-3">Research Interests</h2>
            <ul class="text-sm text-muted space-y-2">
              <li>Management research methodology</li>
              <li>Evidence-based management practice</li>
              <li>Innovation management in SMEs</li>
              <li>Organisational knowledge management</li>
              <li>Business ethics and responsible management</li>
              <li>Entrepreneurship and growth firms</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="card">
            <h2 class="font-bold mb-3">Qualifications</h2>
            <ul class="text-sm text-muted space-y-2">
              <li>PhD, Business and Management, University of Leeds</li>
              <li>MSc Research Methods, London School of Economics</li>
              <li>BSc (Hons) Business Administration, University of Nottingham</li>
              <li>Chartered Fellow, CIPD</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Main content -->
        <div class="md:col-span-2 space-y-8">

          <div>
            <p class="section-label mb-3">Biography</p>
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">About Paul</h2>
            <div class="space-y-4 text-muted">
              <p>Dr. Paul Oliver is Head of Research at Brenkley Doctoral College and chairs the Research Committee. He is responsible for Brenkley Doctoral College's research culture, the development of research capacity among doctoral researchers, and the quality of academic output from the institution. He joined Brenkley Doctoral College after a career spanning business school lecturing, management consultancy, and corporate HR leadership.</p>
              <p>Paul's research interests sit at the intersection of management methodology and organisational practice. His doctoral work examined the conditions under which evidence-based management — the application of research evidence to managerial decision-making — is adopted in small and medium-sized enterprises, and why the uptake remains so limited despite compelling evidence for its effectiveness. This research brought him into close dialogue with questions of management research design, knowledge transfer, and the relationship between academic and practitioner knowledge communities.</p>
              <p>As a supervisor, Paul works across a range of management themes including innovation, entrepreneurship, knowledge management, and business ethics. His methodological strength is in mixed methods design — combining quantitative survey approaches with qualitative case study work to produce findings that are both generalisable and contextually rich. He is particularly interested in supervising researchers who want to use rigorous empirical methods to address questions with direct practical consequences.</p>
              <p>In addition to supervision, Paul leads Brenkley Doctoral College's methods training programme, designing and delivering research design workshops, quantitative and mixed methods modules, and the annual Research Methods Webinar series. He is a member of the British Academy of Management and a reviewer for several peer-reviewed journals in management and organisational studies.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-6">Selected Publications</h2>
            <div class="space-y-4">
              <div class="card">
                <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-foreground mb-1">Oliver, P. (2025). Why management research does not reach managers: Mechanisms and remedies. <em>Academy of Management Learning &amp; Education</em>, 24(1), 67–89.</p>
                <p class="text-sm text-muted">A systematic review and conceptual analysis examining the barriers that prevent management research findings from influencing managerial practice, with a proposed framework for bridging the gap.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="card">
                <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-foreground mb-1">Oliver, P. (2023). Knowledge management in small professional services firms: A mixed methods study. <em>Journal of Knowledge Management</em>, 27(6), 1534–1558.</p>
                <p class="text-sm text-muted">Combining survey data from 180 SMEs with embedded case studies in four firms, this article examines how professional services firms with fewer than fifty employees manage tacit knowledge and expertise retention.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="card">
                <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-foreground mb-1">Oliver, P. &amp; Blower, E. (2022). Wellbeing and performance in knowledge-intensive work: A systematic review. <em>International Journal of Human Resource Management</em>, 33(12), 2401–2428.</p>
                <p class="text-sm text-muted">A co-authored systematic review examining evidence on the relationship between employee wellbeing and performance outcomes in knowledge-intensive professional contexts.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="card">
                <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-foreground mb-1">Oliver, P. (2020). <em>Doing Research in Business and Management: A Practical Guide for Doctoral Researchers.</em> Cheltenham: Edward Elgar Publishing.</p>
                <p class="text-sm text-muted">A research methods textbook designed specifically for professional doctorate and DBA candidates, covering philosophy of social science, research design, and the ethics of practitioner research.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Current Researchers</h2>
            <p class="text-muted mb-4 text-sm">Dr. Oliver currently supervises five doctoral researchers across the DBA and Online PhD programmes. Research areas include innovation adoption in UK manufacturing SMEs, knowledge retention strategies in professional services, ethical decision-making in supply chain management, and digital transformation in NHS procurement.</p>
            <div class="card">
              <p class="text-sm text-muted">Dr. Oliver is open to new enquiries, particularly from researchers interested in business management, innovation, knowledge management, or evidence-based practice. Please contact us to arrange a preliminary conversation.</p>
              <div class="mt-4">
                <a href="/connect" class="btn-primary text-sm">Enquire about supervision</a>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</Layout>
